observations.recommendation:
We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee conduct physical count of all PPEs of the LGU, to include the unserviceable PPE items and duly assign them with inventory stickers/tags for easy and proper identification. Thereafter, prepare the updated RPCPPE based on the result of the physical count and submit the same to the COA Auditor;
The GSO prepare a revised IIRUP to include only the duly identified and/or located unserviceable PPE items based on the result of the actual physical count;
The Disposal Committee dispose the unserviceable PPE items in accordance with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1; and
The Management assign/construct a storage area to be used for storing all unserviceable PPE items prior to its disposal.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Engineer submit to the Municipal Accountant pertinent documents such as, but not limited to, the Statement of Work Accomplished, Certificate of Completion, and Certificate of Project Turnover and Acceptance, of the completed projects;
Based on the submitted documents for completed projects, the Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary journal entries to reclassify the affected CIP accounts into its appropriate infrastructure assets, building or other structures accounts, and set-up the accounts payable pertaining to the amounts due to contractors;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the cost of unused/unutilized construction materials totaling P401,334.58 from the CIP account to the Construction Materials Inventory account;
Management, through the Municipal Engineer, exert effort to negotiate with the alleged owner of the project site for the completion of the project entitled “Construction of Multi-purpose Drying Pavement at Brgy. Lubosan, Lapuyan”. Henceforth, Management properly conduct its detailed engineering activities particularly the conduct of site investigation, survey and site and/or right-of-way acquisitions to prevent similar complications involving project sites/locations; and
The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant establish a proper monitoring and control system to avoid delays by the former’s preparation and submission of pertinent documents of already completed projects which will be used as basis for the latter’s timely reclassification of CIP accounts into the appropriate infrastructure assets, building or other structures accounts, and the setting-up of the accounts payable, particularly at year-end.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees, who are still in active service with the LGU, and to former officers and employees and external debtors for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of their unliquidated cash advances and/or other accountabilities, as applicable, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor. In case of non-settlement, Management cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due to officers and employees, who are still in active service with the LGU and/or file appropriate charges against them;
Send follow-up letter to COA ICFAU pertaining to the Management’s reply to COA ICFAU’s AOM to determine further actions needed;
Strictly comply with pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 relative to the prescribed period for the liquidation of cash advances; and
Through the Municipal Accountant, prepare the schedule of dormant receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers (Annexes 1-3 of COA Circular No. 2016-005) as basis for the request for write-off of dormant accounts. Henceforth, initiate the request for write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended, and the GSO agreed to:
Prepare and maintain the SPCs to record the acquisition, issue/transfer/disposal and the description/information about the semi-expendable property;
Prepare and maintain the RegSPI to record the issue, return, reissue, disposal, and other information about the semi-expendable property if returned and its description/information;
Prepare the IIRUSP to account for all unserviceable semi-expendable property subject to disposal;
Complete the replacement of existing AREs/PARs into ICSs pertaining to tangible items with unit cost below P50,000.00 which were previously classified as PPE. Further, prepare and issue to end-users the ICS in its prescribed form, provide separate control numbers for each ICS for low-valued items and high-valued items, and maintain the same in a sequential manner/order; and
Attend seminars/trainings on Supply and Property Management and other related subject matters.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Review existing lease contracts and make the necessary amendments, particularly the amounts of rental fees, payment schemes, payment schedule, surcharges/penalties for late or non-payment and other pertinent stipulations/conditions, and ensure that the amended stipulations in the lease contracts are all in accordance with the applicable provisions in the existing Municipal Revenue Code;
Review its existing Municipal Revenue Code and consider updating some of its provisions including, but not limited to, the amounts of rental fees, through the passage and enactment of a new/updated Municipal Revenue Code;
Enter into a lease contract/agreement with existing lessees which were found to be without copies of lease contract/agreement on file;
Strictly enforce the surcharge and other penalties for the late or non-payment of rental fees in accordance with the Municipal Revenue Code;
Exert earnest efforts to collect the unpaid balances of stall rental fees of concerned delinquent lessees. Otherwise, cause the cancellation of their lease contracts without prejudice to collection of their unpaid balances and the filing of appropriate charges, as applicable; and
Through the Municipal Accountant, prepare the necessary adjustments to recognize the uncollected rental income; and
Henceforth, properly account receivables and earned income on stall rentals in the LGU’s books of accounts.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Ensure optimal utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;
Fast track the completion and/or implementation of development projects funded out of the current year and continuing appropriations which remained ongoing and/or unimplemented as of year-end. Otherwise, consider the reprogramming of the same which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects;
Consider providing for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects;
Consider initiating the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the middle or end of the year or avail of the procedures for the Early Procurement Activities allowed under existing laws, rules and regulations to avoid delayed and/or non-implementation of projects; and
Realign/reprogram the unexpended/excess balances of continuing appropriations pertaining to fully completed projects to finance other priority development projects of the LGU.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Furnish the Office of the Auditor at the beginning of every calendar year a list of all its on-going PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;
Prepare and submit a complete Quarterly Report on Government PPAs containing not only infrastructure projects but also non-infrastructure PPAs, if any;
For ongoing infrastructure projects without project signboards, immediately post the project signboards in the project sites/locations. Henceforth, comply with the prescribed posting of project signboards for all infrastructure projects; and
Inform the Office of the Auditor within 10 days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted.

Property Custodian prepares the IIRUP which will serve as the basis for the disposal and dropping from the municipality’s books of accounts the unserviceable PPE in order to properly reflect the accurate value of the PPE account in the Financial Statements. Further, dispose of the unserviceable properties in accordance with proper procedures;

Municipal Accountant properly drop from the books the costs of demolished structures;

Management prioritizes the processing and transferring of the title of the parcels of land in the name of the Municipality to establish its legal ownership over said property; 

Municipal Accountant make necessary adjustment regarding the land survey expenditure which was erroneously included in the Land account; and

Management completes the application of the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, which provides for the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies.

We recommended and management agreed to the following:

The Municipal Accountant conduct analysis of the Accounts Payable, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify some accounts payable into its appropriate liability accounts;

The Management further verify the validity of the stale checks particularly those lumped ones so that proper accounting may be made; 

The Municipal Treasurer notify the claimants of the various payables to have it be processed for payment. For those claims whose checks have already become stale, reissue new checks upon request and return of the stale check by the claimant; and 

The Management cause the reversion of accounts that remained outstanding for over two (2) years for which no actual claim has been filed, or which are not covered by perfected contracts on record.

We recommended and management agreed to:

Determine and identify, based on available records and thru confirmation with various agencies, the source agencies of the subject unutilized balances; 

Fully implement those PPAs that are yet to be completed or started;

Identify and direct the focal persons responsible for those PPAs whose status of completion is unknown to verify the actual status of its implementation and provide the necessary documentation that will be used as basis for its liquidation and in the recording in the books by the Municipal Accountant; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to process immediately the return of the unutilized balances of fund transfers to concerned source agencies and/or to the National Treasury, as applicable.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Dispose of the unserviceable properties following proper procedures;
Drop from the books the costs of demolished structures;
Prioritize the processing and transfer of the title of the parcels of land in the name of the Municipality to establish its legal ownership over said property; and
Completes the application of the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, which provides for the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies.

Recommendation:
We recommended and management agreed to the following:
Review and strengthen security measures to prevent similar incidents in the future. This may involve improving access controls, implementing stricter inventory management, or enhancing surveillance;
Evaluate existing procedures for handling accountable forms and revise them as necessary to prevent future losses or unauthorized access;
Provide additional training and awareness programs for personnel involved in handling accountable forms to ensure they understand the importance of security protocols and the potential consequences of mishandling such documents; and
Implement corrective actions based on the findings of the internal investigation. This may include disciplinary measures, process improvements, or other steps to address vulnerabilities.

We recommended the following to management: 

Demand the concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances to effect immediate settlement of cash advances;

Institute appropriate action as provided in COA Circular No. 2012-004 to accountable officers with unsettled cash advances;

Make a follow up letter to COA-ICFAU on the status of liquidation of the Confidential and Intelligence expenses;

Initiate appropriate legal actions to recover from officials and employees who were already separated from the service;

Notify the heirs of the deceased AOs on the existence of unliquidated cash advances of the latter and initiate appropriate action to recover the amount; and

Initiate effort to request authority from the COA to write-off long dormant receivables that are deemed uncollectible as provided in Item 8 of COA Circular No. 2016-005, after all remedies have been exhausted.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Mayor:

Create an appraisal committee which will be tasked to appraise the existing PPEs which were without complete records to reflect the current market value in the books;

Direct the responsible official to prioritize the processing and transfer of the title of the parcel of lands in the name of the Municipality to establish its legal ownership over said property; and

Considers the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 which provides for the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies.

Inventory Committee properly identify specific infrastructures to be reported in the RPCPPE to facilitate its verification and evaluation;

The Property Custodian/GSO:

 Maintain Property Cards for all existing items of PPE;

 Exert effort in determining the details of the transferred infrastructures from the TF for it to be properly appraised and be depreciated, if warranted; and

 Prepare the IIRUP which will serve as the basis in the disposal and dropping from the municipality’s books of accounts in order to properly reflect the accurate value of PPE account in the Financial Statements. Further, dispose the unserviceable properties in accordance with proper procedures;

The Municipal Accountant:

Maintain RPLC and CIPLC; 

Reclassify the expenditures improperly capitalized as PPE;

Reclassify those PPE improperly classified under a different type of PPE to its proper account; and 

Provide depreciation for those depreciable assets that were not depreciated and provide additional depreciation for those that were insufficiently depreciated.

We recommended that the Municipal Government thru the Municipal Mayor, MPDC and GFPS attribute in the GAD Plan and Budget and Accomplishment Report using the HGDG tool those PPAs undertaken by the Municipality as part of its priority agenda and regular programs but not limited to the following:
Heath;
Education;
Disaster mitigation and prevention;
Agriculture and fishery;
Environmental management; and
Others as the GFPS may determine

